<P>
KENNEDY EXPRESSES HIS REGRETS FOR CHAPPAQUIDDICK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Shortly before the 25th anniversary of Chappaquiddick, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy 
Friday issued a statement expressing regret about the incident in which a woman 
drowned in a car he was driving. 
</P>
<P>
 "I bear full responsibility for the tragedy, and I always will," the veteran 
Massachusetts Democrat said in the statement issued from his office in 
Washington regarding the death of Mary Jo Kopechne. 
</P>
<P>
 "I have expressed my remorse to my family, the Kopechne family, and the people 
of Massachusetts. I only wish I had the power to do more to ease the continuing 
pain I feel and that Mr. and Mrs. Kopechne feel for Mary Jo's loss," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Kennedy, 62, was a young senator when he drove off a bridge at Chappaquiddick 
on the island of Martha's Vineyard after a party July 18, 1969. Kopechne 
drowned in the accident but Kennedy left the scene without reporting it. 
</P>
