By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Former Virginia Gov. L. Douglas Wilder has rejected an appeal from Vice 
President Al Gore to drop out of the state's U.S. Senate race, his spokesman 
said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 Glenn Davidson said Wilder met with Gore on Thursday at the White House but 
declined to accept a proposal to step aside and unite the Democratic vote 
behind incumbent Sen. Charles S. Robb in an effort to defeat Republican 
challenger Oliver L. North. 
</P>
<P>
 The Virginia race is shaping up as one of the most controversial of the 
November midterm elections. The seat is also being contested by former 
Republican state Atty. Gen. J. Marshall Coleman. 
</P>
<P>
 Gore issued a statement after his meeting with Wilder, saying: "My purpose in 
inviting my friend Doug Wilder to come for a visit was to tell him in person 
that I hope he will end up supporting the candidacy of Sen. Robb for 
reelection." 
</P>
<P>
 But Wilder said: "I told the vice president I was committed to running. That 
is final, complete." 
</P>
<P>
 Wilder, the grandchild of slaves, was the first black to be elected a state 
governor. He has a longrunning and bitter personal rivalry with Robb. 
</P>
