<HEADLINE>
<P>
REGULATORS CLOSE BANK OF SAN PEDRO; FINANCE: INSUFFICIENT CAPITAL CITED. HOME 
BANK OF SIGNAL HILL TO ACQUIRE ASSETS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JESUS SANCHEZ, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 State banking regulators Friday closed Bank of San Pedro, which had six 
branches and $123.4 million in assets, after real estate loans and operating 
losses had reduced the financial institution's capital below acceptable levels. 
</P>
<P>
 Home Bank of Signal Hill will acquire $22.1 million of the failed bank's 
assets and assume $82.2 million in insured deposits. The two Bank of San Pedro 
branches in San Pedro will reopen as Home Bank offices. The bank's headquarters 
office and branches in Avalon, Gardena and Long Beach were closed by state 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
 Home Bank will decide whether to hire back Bank of San Pedro employees. 
</P>
<P>
 "Bank of San Pedro was operating in an unsafe manner, which necessitated the 
closure as a protection to depositors and creditors," James E. Gilleran, the 
state's banking superintendent, said in a statement.  
</P>
<P>
 "I am very pleased that an acquisition was successfully negotiated, because it 
provides assurance to most depositors of Bank of San Pedro that their banking 
business will continue without interruption," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 About $6.4 million in 210 Bank of San Pedro accounts exceeded the federal 
insurance limit of $100,000 and will not be assumed by Home Bank. Gilleran 
placed the bank under the receivership of the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. 
</P>
<P>
 Bank of San Pedro had been considered a "problem bank" since 1987, regulators 
said. The bank has sustained more than $4 million in operating losses since 
1992. 
</P>
<P>
 Regulators determined that the bank was not viable after real estate and 
commercial loan losses had reduced its capital to $1.2 million. In addition, 
they said, the financial institution had been losing $200,000 a month. 
</P>
<P>
 Bank officials had tried to raise capital in negotiations with private parties 
and also tried to sell additional stock, the regulators said. However, those 
efforts failed to draw sufficient investment to bring the bank to acceptable 
capital levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
