<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VALLEY FOCUS: CANOGA PARK; YOUTH GIVEN TICKETS TO WORLD CUP FINAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MAKI BECKER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Nine-year-old Robert Perez and his dad, Carlos Ramon, were one of the luckiest 
father-son teams in the San Fernando Valley on Friday -- Robert was awarded a 
pair of tickets to the World Cup final between Brazil and Italy. 
</P>
<P>
 The Syrvet Corp. of Des Moines, Iowa, donated the tickets to Catholic 
Charities located in Canoga Park, an organization that provides emergency 
assistance and works with the elderly, refugees, immigrants and at-risk 
youths.Catholic Charities, in turn, presented the tickets -- worth $180 each -- 
to Robert, a Van Nuys soccer fan. 
</P>
<P>
 Catholic Charities of Los Angeles is awarding three pairs of World Cup tickets 
to youngsters who otherwise would not be able to afford to go, said Greg 
Stuart, the agency's youth services director. Ticket recipients are asked to 
take a member of their family to the match. 
</P>
<P>
 "They called me and said, 'You're going to the World Cup final,' " Robert 
said, but he didn't believe he had actually won at first. 
</P>
<P>
 Once he was convinced he had won, Robert's mother, Marian Ramon, said her son 
was ecstatic. "He was jumping up and down." 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm really excited," Robert said. "Brazil is my favorite team." MAKI BECKER 
</P>
