<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: KEENAN QUITS STUNNED RANGERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Mike Keenan, who last month coached the New York Rangers to their first 
Stanley Cup in 54 years, shocked the team Friday by saying he was leaving 
because of a "breach of contractual obligations." 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm here to announce that I'm no longer the coach of the New York Rangers," 
Keenan said. "The obligations were not fulfilled" by the Rangers, he said. 
"There's quite a significant amount of money involved." 
</P>
<P>
 Madison Square Garden Corp., which owns the team, said it was "stunned at the 
capricious actions of Mr. Keenan and his agent, (Robert) Campbell, and will 
take all necessary actions to preserve all of its rights." Football  
</P>
<P>
 The Atlanta Falcons signed wide receiver Ricky Sanders to a one-year contract, 
three months after voiding a longer and more lucrative contract because of a 
shoulder injury. . . . The San Francisco 49ers signed center Bart Oates from 
the New York Giants. . . . Detroit signed Tampa Bay free agent linebacker 
Broderick Thomas and re-signed wide receiver Aubrey Matthews. . . . Cleveland 
waived guard Houston Hoover after he failed to pass his physical. The Browns 
also signed guard Mike Schad, an unrestricted free agent from Philadelphia and 
agreed to contract terms with free agent linebacker Percy Snow. Track  
</P>
<P>
 Jon Drummond won the 100-meter dash in the TSB Games London Grand Prix meet as 
world and Olympic champion Linford Christie pulled up clutching his right 
hamstring. Drummond won with a time of 10.03 seconds. Christie finished second 
at 10.07. Cycling  
</P>
<P>
 Three-time champion Miguel Indurain of Spain finished more than seven minutes 
behind the 12th stage winner, Richard Virenque of France, but was still able to 
push his lead to 7:56 over Tony Rominger of Switzerland, his main rival, in the 
Tour de France. Tennis  
</P>
<P>
 Jim Courier defeated Richard Krajicek, 6-4, 6-3, 6-3, and Pete Sampras beat 
Jacco Eltingh, 6-2, 6-2, 6-0, to give the United States a 2-0 lead against the 
Netherlands in the best-of-five Davis Cup quarterfinal at Rotterdam. 
</P>
<P>
 The United States can eliminate the Dutch today with a victory in doubles. 
</P>
<P>
 Third-seeded MaliVai Washington and fifth-seeded Wally Masur reached the 
semifinals of the U.S. Pro Tennis Championships at Brookline, Mass. Washington 
defeated George Bezecny, 6-0, 6-2, to set up a semifinal against either Patrick 
McEnroe or Jimmy Arias. Masur edged David Nainkin, 7-5, 7-6 (12-10), and will 
face the winner of the quarterfinal match between top-seeded Ivan Lendl and 
Mats Wilander. Miscellany  
</P>
<P>
 Harris County, Tex., officials dropped a drunken driving charge against 
Houston Rocket Coach Rudy Tomjanovich because of insufficient evidence. . . . 
Detroit police are investigating a woman's allegation that New Jersey Net 
forward Derrick Coleman raped her last week in a hotel room. . . . Robby Gordon 
set a track qualifying record with a lap of 110.191 m.p.h. to win the 
provisional pole for Sunday's Toronto Molson-Indy, ahead of Nigel Mansell. . . 
. Detroit Red Wing forward Bob Probert, 29, was injured after being thrown from 
his motorcycle during a collision with a car. . . . UCLA guard Tyus Edney and 
Duke center Cherokee Parks were among 12 players to make the final cut for the 
U.S. national team that will play in the Goodwill Games in St. Petersburg, 
Russia, starting July 23. . . . L.A. lawyer John Argue, architect of the bid 
that brought the 1984 Summer Olympics to Southern California, will be presented 
the Olympic Order award tonight at the Amateur Athletic Foundation. . . . The 
Professional Bowlers Assn.'s $100,000 Active West Thunderbird Open will begin 
today at Ontario. 
</P>
</TEXT>
